<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06120183 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06120183 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Associated Press; Justin Whorley, 10, rummages in theGolden Spur Mobile Home Park pool in Andover, Kan., oblivious to the car thathad been tossed there Friday by a tornado. PHOTO: Scott Hansen pulls a garbagecart full of his brother's personal items from the mobile home park.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  AID; HOMELESS; VICTIM; WEATHER; DISASTER; KANSAS  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Townspeople collected clothes and opened their hearts to victims of a tornadothat killed 14 people. Survivors sang, &quot;We'll understand it better by and by,&quot;at a memorial service.;    &quot;Friends, we're not defeated, the Rev. Steve Weldontold worshipers. &quot;We are not without hope. We have not lost the battle.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  AID POURING IN FOR THE HOMELESS AFTER TORNADOES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The Andover Methodist Church was crammed with clothing donated to the 1,500residents who were left homeless by the twister that flattened a mobile homepark and destroyed 88 houses and 11 businesses Friday night.;    In a bigmeeting room, workers sorted 3,000 pounds of clothing donated by people,churches and businesses. Andover Primary School's gymnasium was filled withrows of donated food.;    &quot;I bet some stores aren't stocked this well,&quot; RedCross volunteer Marvin Keeler said.;    Fourteen residents of the town's40-acre Golden Spur Mobile Home Park were killed when a tornado destroyed 226trailers and heavily damaged 15. Earlier reports had placed the town's deathtoll at 20.;    Three Wichita residents were killed and two other fatalitieswere reported in outlying Kansas counties -- bringing the Kansas total fromthe storm to 19. Three people were killed just over the state line inOklahoma, for a total of 22 dead.;    The Kansas count had been reported at20, but officials discovered that a Wichita man who was killed in Oklahomawhile returning from a business trip had been counted in both states.;   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev sent condolences today to PresidentGeorge Bush for victims of the tornadoes, the news agency Tass reported inMoscow.;    Kansas Gov. Joan Finney today asked President Bush for help inrecovering from the tornadoes, and the White House said Bush would act quicklyon a formal disaster declaration.;    The Andover School Board suspendedclasses today because school buildings were being used in the recoveryeffort.;    The town's lone civil defense siren, only about a quarter milefrom the demolished mobile home park, never sounded. Local officials said theytried four times in the 20 minutes before the tornado struck to make it work.;   In response, authorities said police and fire units sped through the area,using sirens and loudspeakers to notify residents.;    Some survivors,however, said they were not aware of the police and fire warnings.;    Duringthe memorial, worshipers sang the hymn &quot;We'll Understand It Better By and By.&quot;Another hymn told of God being a &quot;shelter from the stormy blast.&quot;;    Fewerthan 100 people attended, probably because victims wanted to use the remainingdaylight to look for belongings in the rubble, organizers said.;    The newlyhomeless continued to find lost treasures under the mobile home frames, whichwere twisted like giant steel pretzels.;    &quot;We just found our cat. She'salive,&quot; said Renee Berggren. &quot;She had been bulldozed under.&quot;;    &quot;There's thequilt I made! I just don't believe it!&quot; Kathy Schultz shouted to a friend,pulling the colorful item from the debris.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Andover, Kan.  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910429  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATU